english:
  title: On the Proper Etiquette for the Maternal Grandfather
  author: Kim Bu-sik
  language: eng
  text: |-
    When Emperor Gaozu of Han first brought peace to the realm, he received his father, the Grand Progenitor, every five days. The Grand Progenitor's household steward counseled him, saying: "There cannot be two suns in heaven, nor two rulers upon earth. Though the Emperor is your son, he is the ruler of men. Though you are his father, you remain his subject. How then can we have the ruler bow to the subject?"

    Emperor Gaozu, finding wisdom in these words, issued a decree: "Among all human relations, none is closer than father and son. When a father possesses the realm, it passes to his son. When a son possesses the realm, he honors his father. This is the perfection of human virtue. Now, though the princes and ministers have elevated me as Emperor, my father lacks a proper title. Therefore, I bestow upon my father the title of Supreme Emperor. By this logic, even the father of a Son of Heaven, lacking an honorific title, cannot require the ruler to bow."

    Consider the case of Fu Wan, father of the Empress under Emperor Xian of Han. The scholar Zheng Xuan argued: "When the father-in-law resides in the capital, he should observe the rites of a subject. Yet when the Empress retires to her private quarters or visits her parents' home, he should be received as a father. Thus Fu Wan participated in court audiences as a minister, yet when the Empress was within the palace, she bowed to him as a daughter."

    Likewise, when the officials of Eastern Jin debated the proper etiquette for the mother of Emperor Mu toward her father, opinions scattered in disorder. The scholar Xu Shan, following Zheng Xuan's reasoning, declared: "In the court, observe the rites between ruler and subject. In private quarters, preserve the intimacy of parent and child. This is the path of supreme harmony."

    Moreover, even the father of the Wei Emperor, Prince You of Yan, when submitting memorials, referred to himself as a subject. Though father and son share the deepest bond, propriety maintained such distance. How much more so for one's maternal grandfather!

    Consulting the rites of kinship mourning, the maternal grandparents require only five months of mourning—a degree of kinship far removed from one's own parents. How then could such a person contradict the proper order through excessive familiarity? Therefore, the maternal grandfather should refer to himself as subject in formal memorials, observe the rites of ruler and subject in court, yet be greeted as family within the inner chambers. Thus both public duty and private affection find their proper place.

    When this memorial reached the throne, the king sent an attendant to consult with Chief Counselor Ja Gyeom. Ja Gyeom responded: "Though I possess little wisdom, observing the reasoning of Kim Bu-sik, I find it expresses the judgment of all the realm. Had this man not spoken, I would have fallen into grave error. I humbly request we follow his counsel without hesitation." The king, convinced, issued a decree approving the proposal.
  footnotes:
    - The Chinese historical examples (Emperor Gaozu, Fu Wan, the Eastern Jin court, and Prince You of Yan) serve to establish a clear philosophical precedent for resolving questions of propriety in a Confucian court. These are not merely historical references but constitute authoritative models for proper conduct.
    - The concept of 'public duty' (공의) versus 'private affection' (사은) represents a core tension in Confucian governance—the resolution proposed here, that both may coexist in different contexts, reflects sophisticated political philosophy about maintaining ritual propriety while honoring familial relationships.
